Here is a thorough reference for the **OpenTelemetry 0.29 Rust API**, covering all the areas you asked about. The version compatibility matrix for `opentelemetry 0.29` is:

| Crate | Version |
|---|---|
| `opentelemetry` | `0.29` |
| `opentelemetry_sdk` | `0.29` |
| `opentelemetry-otlp` | `0.29` |
| `tracing-opentelemetry` | `0.30` |

---

## 1. Cargo.toml Dependencies

```toml
[dependencies]
opentelemetry        = { version = "0.29", features = ["trace", "metrics"] }
opentelemetry_sdk    = { version = "0.29", features = ["trace", "metrics"] }
opentelemetry-otlp   = { version = "0.29", features = ["trace", "metrics", "grpc-tonic"] }
# For HTTP instead of gRPC:
# opentelemetry-otlp = { version = "0.29", features = ["trace", "metrics", "http-proto", "reqwest-blocking-client"] }
tracing-opentelemetry = { version = "0.30" }
tracing              = "0.1"
tracing-subscriber   = { version = "0.3", features = ["registry", "env-filter", "fmt"] }
```

**Feature flags in `opentelemetry-otlp` 0.29:**
- Transport: `grpc-tonic`, `http-proto`, `http-json`
- Signal: `trace`, `metrics`, `logs`
- HTTP client: `reqwest-blocking-client`, `reqwest-client`, `hyper-client`
- Compression: `gzip-tonic`, `zstd-tonic`
- TLS: `tls`, `tls-roots`, `tls-webpki-roots`
- Default features (enabled automatically): `http-proto`, `reqwest-blocking-client`, `trace`, `metrics`, `logs`, `internal-logs`

Note: `grpc-tonic` is **not** a default feature as of 0.28+. You must explicitly enable it.

---

## 2. Creating OTLP Exporters

### gRPC (tonic) Exporter

```rust
use opentelemetry_otlp::SpanExporter;

// Span exporter (traces) -- gRPC
let span_exporter = SpanExporter::builder()
    .with_tonic()
    .build()?;

// Metric exporter -- gRPC
let metric_exporter = opentelemetry_otlp::MetricExporter::builder()
    .with_tonic()
    .build()?;
```

With custom configuration:

```rust
use opentelemetry_otlp::{SpanExporter, WithTonicConfig, WithExportConfig};
use std::time::Duration;

let span_exporter = SpanExporter::builder()
    .with_tonic()
    .with_endpoint("https://collector.example.com:4317")
    .with_timeout(Duration::from_secs(10))
    .with_metadata(metadata)                     // tonic::metadata::MetadataMap
    .with_tls_config(tls_config)                 // tonic::transport::ClientTlsConfig
    .build()?;
```

### HTTP (protobuf) Exporter

```rust
use opentelemetry_otlp::{SpanExporter, Protocol, WithExportConfig};

let span_exporter = SpanExporter::builder()
    .with_http()
    .with_protocol(Protocol::HttpBinary)   // or Protocol::HttpJson with "http-json" feature
    .build()?;

let metric_exporter = opentelemetry_otlp::MetricExporter::builder()
    .with_http()
    .with_protocol(Protocol::HttpBinary)
    .with_endpoint("http://localhost:4318/v1/metrics")
    .build()?;
```

### Default Exporter (no transport specified)

The official `basic-otlp` example shows that you can just call `.build()` without specifying a transport, which uses whatever default features are enabled:

```rust
let exporter = SpanExporter::builder()
    .build()
    .expect("Failed to create span exporter");
```

---

## 3. Setting Up SdkTracerProvider

```rust
use opentelemetry_sdk::trace::SdkTracerProvider;
use opentelemetry_sdk::Resource;
use opentelemetry::global;

fn init_tracer_provider() -> SdkTracerProvider {
    let exporter = opentelemetry_otlp::SpanExporter::builder()
        .with_tonic()
        .build()
        .expect("Failed to create span exporter");

    let provider = SdkTracerProvider::builder()
        .with_batch_exporter(exporter)          // batched (recommended for production)
        // .with_simple_exporter(exporter)       // synchronous (useful for testing)
        .with_resource(
            Resource::builder()
                .with_service_name("my-service")
                .build(),
        )
        // .with_sampler(opentelemetry_sdk::trace::Sampler::AlwaysOn)
        // .with_span_limits(opentelemetry_sdk::trace::SpanLimits::default())
        .build();

    // Set as global provider -- accepts anything implementing TracerProvider + Send + Sync + 'static
    global::set_tracer_provider(provider.clone());

    provider  // KEEP a handle for shutdown
}
```

**Key `TracerProviderBuilder` methods** (all on `SdkTracerProvider::builder()`):
- `with_batch_exporter(exporter)` -- adds a `BatchSpanProcessor`
- `with_simple_exporter(exporter)` -- adds a `SimpleSpanProcessor`
- `with_span_processor(processor)` -- adds a custom `SpanProcessor`
- `with_resource(resource)` -- associates a `Resource` (additive across calls)
- `with_sampler(sampler)` -- sets the sampling strategy
- `with_id_generator(generator)` -- custom trace/span ID generation
- `with_span_limits(limits)` -- sets span limits
- `build()` -- produces `SdkTracerProvider`

**Important change from pre-0.28:** The type was renamed from `TracerProvider` to `SdkTracerProvider`. The old name no longer exists in the SDK.

**Resource builder (0.28+ change):**
```rust
// OLD (pre-0.28):
Resource::default().with_attributes([KeyValue::new("service.name", "foo")]);

// NEW (0.28+):
Resource::builder()
    .with_service_name("foo")
    .with_attribute(KeyValue::new("key", "value"))
    .build();
```

---

## 4. Setting Up SdkMeterProvider (Metrics)

```rust
use opentelemetry_sdk::metrics::SdkMeterProvider;
use opentelemetry_sdk::Resource;
use opentelemetry::global;

fn init_meter_provider() -> SdkMeterProvider {
    let exporter = opentelemetry_otlp::MetricExporter::builder()
        .with_tonic()
        .build()
        .expect("Failed to create metric exporter");

    let provider = SdkMeterProvider::builder()
        .with_periodic_exporter(exporter)       // auto-wraps in PeriodicReader (60s default)
        .with_resource(
            Resource::builder()
                .with_service_name("my-service")
                .build(),
        )
        .build();

    global::set_meter_provider(provider.clone());

    provider  // KEEP a handle for shutdown
}
```

**Key `MeterProviderBuilder` methods:**
- `with_periodic_exporter(exporter)` -- wraps in `PeriodicReader`, 60s interval (customizable via `OTEL_METRIC_EXPORT_INTERVAL` env var)
- `with_reader(reader)` -- attach a custom `MetricReader` (e.g., a manually-built `PeriodicReader`)
- `with_resource(resource)` -- associates a `Resource`
- `with_view(fn)` -- register a view closure `Fn(&Instrument) -> Option<Stream>`
- `build()` -- produces `SdkMeterProvider`

For custom interval, build the `PeriodicReader` manually:
```rust
use opentelemetry_sdk::metrics::PeriodicReader;
use std::time::Duration;

let reader = PeriodicReader::builder(exporter)
    .with_interval(Duration::from_secs(15))
    .build();

let provider = SdkMeterProvider::builder()
    .with_reader(reader)
    .with_resource(Resource::builder().with_service_name("my-service").build())
    .build();
```

**Important 0.28+ change:** `PeriodicReader::builder(exporter)` no longer requires a runtime parameter. It was previously `.builder(exporter, runtime::Tokio)`. In 0.28+ it spawns its own background thread.

---

## 5. Creating Metrics Instruments

```rust
use opentelemetry::{global, KeyValue};

let meter = global::meter("my-service");

// Counter (monotonically increasing)
let counter = meter
    .u64_counter("http.requests.total")
    .with_description("Total HTTP requests")
    .with_unit("requests")
    .build();

counter.add(1, &[KeyValue::new("method", "GET"), KeyValue::new("status", "200")]);

// Histogram (distribution of values)
let histogram = meter
    .f64_histogram("http.request.duration")
    .with_description("HTTP request duration in seconds")
    .with_unit("s")
    .with_boundaries(vec![0.005, 0.01, 0.025, 0.05, 0.1, 0.25, 0.5, 1.0, 2.5, 5.0, 10.0])
    .build();

histogram.record(0.042, &[KeyValue::new("method", "GET")]);

// Gauge (current value, can go up or down)
let gauge = meter
    .f64_gauge("system.cpu.utilization")
    .with_description("CPU utilization percentage")
    .with_unit("1")
    .build();

gauge.record(0.75, &[KeyValue::new("cpu", "0")]);

// UpDownCounter (can increase or decrease)
let updown = meter
    .i64_up_down_counter("http.active_connections")
    .with_description("Number of active connections")
    .build();

updown.add(1, &[]);   // connection opened
updown.add(-1, &[]);  // connection closed

// Observable counter (callback-based)
let _observable = meter
    .u64_observable_counter("process.cpu.time")
    .with_description("Total CPU time")
    .with_callback(|observer| {
        observer.observe(12345, &[KeyValue::new("state", "user")]);
    })
    .build();
```

**Available instrument creation methods on `Meter`:**

| Method | Returns Builder For |
|---|---|
| `u64_counter(name)` | `Counter<u64>` |
| `f64_counter(name)` | `Counter<f64>` |
| `i64_up_down_counter(name)` | `UpDownCounter<i64>` |
| `f64_up_down_counter(name)` | `UpDownCounter<f64>` |
| `u64_gauge(name)` | `Gauge<u64>` |
| `f64_gauge(name)` | `Gauge<f64>` |
| `i64_gauge(name)` | `Gauge<i64>` |
| `u64_histogram(name)` | `Histogram<u64>` |
| `f64_histogram(name)` | `Histogram<f64>` |
| `u64_observable_counter(name)` | `ObservableCounter<u64>` |
| `f64_observable_counter(name)` | `ObservableCounter<f64>` |
| `u64_observable_gauge(name)` | `ObservableGauge<u64>` |
| `f64_observable_gauge(name)` | `ObservableGauge<f64>` |
| `i64_observable_gauge(name)` | `ObservableGauge<i64>` |
| `i64_observable_up_down_counter(name)` | `ObservableUpDownCounter<i64>` |
| `f64_observable_up_down_counter(name)` | `ObservableUpDownCounter<f64>` |

All builders support `.with_description(str)` and `.with_unit(str)`. `HistogramBuilder` additionally supports `.with_boundaries(Vec<f64>)`. Observable builders support `.with_callback(fn)`.

---

## 6. Creating the tracing-opentelemetry Layer

```rust
use tracing_opentelemetry;
use tracing_subscriber::prelude::*;
use tracing_subscriber::{EnvFilter, Registry};
use opentelemetry_sdk::trace::SdkTracerProvider;

// The provider should already be created (see section 3)
let tracer_provider: SdkTracerProvider = init_tracer_provider();
let tracer = tracer_provider.tracer("my-service");

// Create the OTel layer
let otel_layer = tracing_opentelemetry::layer()
    .with_tracer(tracer);

// Wire into tracing-subscriber
tracing_subscriber::registry()
    .with(otel_layer)
    .with(tracing_subscriber::fmt::layer().with_filter(EnvFilter::new("info")))
    .init();
```

The `layer()` function signature (in `tracing-opentelemetry` 0.30):
```rust
pub fn layer<S>() -> OpenTelemetryLayer<S, NoopTracer>
where
    S: Subscriber + for<'span> LookupSpan<'span>,
```

It returns a `NoopTracer` layer that you then configure with `.with_tracer(tracer)`.

**Available configuration methods on `OpenTelemetryLayer`:**
- `.with_tracer(tracer)` -- set the OTel tracer (required)
- `.with_location(bool)` -- include file/module/line (default: true)
- `.with_tracked_inactivity(bool)` -- track busy/idle time (default: true)
- `.with_threads(bool)` -- include thread name/ID (default: true)
- `.with_level(bool)` -- include tracing level as attribute (default: false)
- `.with_target(bool)` -- include span target (default: true)
- `.with_error_records_to_exceptions(bool)` -- map error records to OTel exceptions (default: true)
- `.with_error_fields_to_exceptions(bool)` -- map error fields to exceptions (default: true)
- `.with_error_events_to_exceptions(bool)` -- map error events to exceptions (default: true)
- `.with_error_events_to_status(bool)` -- error events set span status (default: true)
- `.with_context_activation(bool)` -- activate OTel context on span entry (default: true)

---

## 7. Shutdown / Flush

Providers must be explicitly shut down. **You must retain a clone** of each provider handle.

```rust
// Shutdown all providers (order: traces, metrics, logs)
let mut errors = Vec::new();

if let Err(e) = tracer_provider.shutdown() {
    errors.push(format!("tracer: {e}"));
}

if let Err(e) = meter_provider.shutdown() {
    errors.push(format!("meter: {e}"));
}

// For force-flush without full shutdown:
tracer_provider.force_flush()?;
meter_provider.force_flush()?;

// With timeout:
tracer_provider.shutdown_with_timeout(Duration::from_secs(5))?;
```

**Key 0.28+ change:** The old `opentelemetry::global::shutdown_tracer_provider()` global function was removed. You must now hold a reference to the `SdkTracerProvider` and call `.shutdown()` on it directly.

**Shutdown method signatures:**
- `SdkTracerProvider::shutdown(&self) -> OTelSdkResult`
- `SdkTracerProvider::shutdown_with_timeout(&self, Duration) -> OTelSdkResult`
- `SdkTracerProvider::force_flush(&self) -> OTelSdkResult`
- `SdkMeterProvider::shutdown(&self) -> OTelSdkResult`
- `SdkMeterProvider::shutdown_with_timeout(&self, Duration) -> OTelSdkResult`
- `SdkMeterProvider::force_flush(&self) -> OTelSdkResult`

---

## 8. Complete Working Example

Putting it all together, here is the canonical initialization pattern for opentelemetry 0.29:

```rust
use opentelemetry::{global, KeyValue};
use opentelemetry_otlp::{SpanExporter, MetricExporter};
use opentelemetry_sdk::metrics::SdkMeterProvider;
use opentelemetry_sdk::trace::SdkTracerProvider;
use opentelemetry_sdk::Resource;
use std::sync::OnceLock;
use tracing_subscriber::prelude::*;
use tracing_subscriber::EnvFilter;

fn resource() -> Resource {
    static RES: OnceLock<Resource> = OnceLock::new();
    RES.get_or_init(|| {
        Resource::builder()
            .with_service_name("my-service")
            .with_attribute(KeyValue::new("service.version", "0.1.0"))
            .build()
    })
    .clone()
}

fn init_traces() -> SdkTracerProvider {
    let exporter = SpanExporter::builder()
        .with_tonic()
        .build()
        .expect("span exporter");

    SdkTracerProvider::builder()
        .with_batch_exporter(exporter)
        .with_resource(resource())
        .build()
}

fn init_metrics() -> SdkMeterProvider {
    let exporter = MetricExporter::builder()
        .with_tonic()
        .build()
        .expect("metric exporter");

    SdkMeterProvider::builder()
        .with_periodic_exporter(exporter)
        .with_resource(resource())
        .build()
}

fn main() -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
    // 1. Build providers
    let tracer_provider = init_traces();
    let meter_provider = init_metrics();

    // 2. Set globals
    global::set_tracer_provider(tracer_provider.clone());
    global::set_meter_provider(meter_provider.clone());

    // 3. Wire tracing-opentelemetry layer
    let tracer = tracer_provider.tracer("my-service");
    let otel_layer = tracing_opentelemetry::layer().with_tracer(tracer);

    let fmt_layer = tracing_subscriber::fmt::layer()
        .with_filter(EnvFilter::new("info"));

    tracing_subscriber::registry()
        .with(otel_layer)
        .with(fmt_layer)
        .init();

    // 4. Use metrics
    let meter = global::meter("my-service");
    let counter = meter.u64_counter("requests").build();
    counter.add(1, &[KeyValue::new("path", "/api")]);

    // 5. Shutdown
    tracer_provider.shutdown()?;
    meter_provider.shutdown()?;

    Ok(())
}
```

---

## 9. Summary of Breaking Changes (0.27 -> 0.28 -> 0.29)

| Area | Old (pre-0.28) | New (0.28+/0.29) |
|---|---|---|
| Tracer provider type | `TracerProvider` | `SdkTracerProvider` |
| Meter provider type | Already `SdkMeterProvider` | `SdkMeterProvider` (unchanged) |
| Resource creation | `Resource::default().with_attributes(...)` | `Resource::builder().with_service_name(...).build()` |
| Batch exporter | `.with_batch_exporter(exp, runtime::Tokio)` | `.with_batch_exporter(exp)` (no runtime param) |
| PeriodicReader | `PeriodicReader::builder(exp, runtime::Tokio)` | `PeriodicReader::builder(exp)` (no runtime param) |
| Global shutdown | `global::shutdown_tracer_provider()` | `provider.shutdown()` on retained handle |
| Default OTLP transport | `grpc-tonic` was default | `http-proto` + `reqwest-blocking-client` are default |
| `set_tracer_provider` | Same function name | `global::set_tracer_provider(provider)` -- accepts `P: TracerProvider + Send + Sync + 'static` |
| `set_meter_provider` | Same function name | `global::set_meter_provider(provider)` -- accepts `P: MeterProvider + Send + Sync + 'static` |

